{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568255"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:12:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:12:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19703"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.87,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10547"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29893"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with increasing drowsiness following a total knee replacement three days ago. She has a history of moderate chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and takes regular tiotropium and budesonide/formoterol. She is receiving regular oxycodone for post-operative pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy but rousable. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 8/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her chest is clear on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial blood gas results reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.28 (7.35-7.45)\u003Cbr /\u003EPaCO2 60 mmHg (35-45)\u003Cbr /\u003EPaO2 60 mmHg (80-100)\u003Cbr /\u003EHCO3 30 mmol/L (22-26)\u003Cbr /\u003EBase excess +2 mmol/L (-2 to +2)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute COPD exacerbation","Opioid-induced respiratory depression","Pneumonia","Pulmonary embolism","Sleep apnoea"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eopioid-induced respiratory depression (OIRD) \u003C/strong\u003Ein the post-operative period. The combination of drowsiness, bradypnoea (respiratory rate 8/min), and respiratory acidosis in the context of recent opioid administration strongly suggests this diagnosis. Although beyond the scope of this question, the Alveolar to arterial oxygen gradient (A-a gradient) is relatively normal at around 15mmHg. This is supportive of hypoventilation (as occurs in OIRD) as a cause for this patient\u0027s respiratory failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOpioid-induced respiratory depression is a significant post-operative complication, particularly in patients with underlying respiratory disease. The arterial blood gas shows respiratory acidosis with mild compensatory metabolic alkalosis, consistent with acute hypoventilation. The patient\u0027s age and COPD increase her risk of this complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute COPD exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with increased dyspnoea, cough, and sputum production. While this patient has underlying COPD, the presentation is more consistent with opioid effects, particularly given the timing post-surgery and the bradypnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with fever, productive cough, and focal chest findings on examination. The clear chest examination and absence of fever make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with tachypnoea, tachycardia, and pleuritic chest pain. The blood gas would usually show respiratory alkalosis due to hyperventilation, not the respiratory acidosis seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESleep apnoea\u003C/strong\u003E, while a possible contributing factor, would not explain these findings during waking hours. Additionally, sleep apnoea typically causes intermittent episodes of apnoea rather than persistent bradypnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should focus on reducing opioid doses, considering alternative pain management strategies, and close monitoring. Naloxone may be required if respiratory depression worsens, though careful titration is needed to avoid complete reversal of analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid-induced respiratory depression commonly presents with drowsiness and bradypnoea in post-operative patients.","Risk factors for opioid-induced respiratory depression include underlying COPD, advanced age, and sleep disorders.","Respiratory acidosis with mild compensatory metabolic alkalosis is characteristic of opioid-induced respiratory depression."],"references":["Boom et al. Non-analgesic effects of opioids: opioid-induced respiratory depression, Curr Pharm Des, 2012. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22747535/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-01T13:04:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-01T13:04:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12479"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com